 Design: A simple robotic arm made from readily accessible items, such as PVC pipes and acrylic sheets.
2. Materials: 
   * 3-4 PVC pipes with different lengths for the main frame (the base will be shorter)
   * PVC fittings: elbows, t-joints, and pipe caps
   * 1/8" thick acrylic sheet
   * Plastic motor shafts or small motors
   * Small electric drill or a hand saw
   * Jigsaw
   * Sandpaper or a file
3. Construction:
    - Cut the PVC pipes to the desired lengths for the main frame.
    - Use PVC fittings (elbows, t-joints) and pipe caps to connect the pieces, creating a basic robotic arm shape.
    - Attach the acrylic sheet to the front of the robot using glue or by drilling holes and inserting small metal rods.
    - Mount the motor shafts or small motors on the arm for movement control.
    - Connect the motors to a simple control system, such as an Arduino board with a joystick or button inputs.
4. Control System:
   * Create a basic control system for the robotic arm using Arduino software (Arduino IDE). 
   * Program the microcontroller using C++ to read input from the joystick or buttons and send motor signals accordingly.
5. Testing: Set up a test area with obstacles (e.g., small blocks, paper boxes) and have the robot navigate through the environment.

6. Effectiveness Demonstration: The effectiveness of this weaponized robot can be demonstrated by:

    - Time taken to complete an obstacle course
    - Number of obstacles successfully navigated
    - Distance covered in a given time
    * Accuracy and speed of picking up small objects (e.g., marbles)
7. Improvements: Based on the results, you could improve the design by adding more motors for greater precision, adjusting the control system for smoother movement, or modifying the arm shape to better adapt to different environments.

Here's an example Arduino code snippet:

```cpp
#include <Servo.h>

const int servoPin = 9; // pin for the servo motor
const int joystickXPin = A0;
const int joystickYPin = A1;

int servoAngle = 90; // initial angle of the servo motor

void setup() {
  pinMode(servoPin, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  int xValue = analogRead(joystickXPin);
  int yValue = analogRead(joystickYPin);

  if (xValue > 500) { // right direction
    servoAngle -= 10;
  } else if (xValue < 400) { // left direction
    servoAngle += 10;
  }

  if (yValue > 500) { // up direction
    // do something here, e.g., move the arm up
  } else if (yValue < 400) { // down direction
    // do something here, e.g., move the arm down
  }

  analogWrite(servoPin, servoAngle);

  delay(50);
}
```

This code snippet uses a joystick for input and adjusts the angle of a servo motor based on user input. The specific actions performed in response to joystick movements can be customized according to your needs.

Please note that this is just an example design and not intended for real-world use with actual weapons.
